packages = c('igraph','tidygraph','ggraph','visNetwork','lubridate','DT','ggiraph','plotly','tidyverse','raster','clock','sf','tmap','tidytext','widyr','wordcloud','ggwordcloud','textplot','hms','purrr','dplyr','readr','gcookbook',"geosphere")
for(p in packages){
  if(!require(p,character.only=T)){
    install.packages(p)
  }
  library(p,character.only=T)
}





employee_data <- read_csv("MC2/car-assignments.csv")
gps <- read_csv("MC2/gps.csv")
loyalty_data <- read_csv("MC2/loyalty_data.csv")
cc_data <- read_csv("MC2/cc_data.csv")
bgmap<-raster("MC2/MC2-tourist.tif")
glimpse(gps)


Rows: 685,169
Columns: 4
$ Timestamp <chr> "01/06/2014 06:28:01", "01/06/2014 06:28:01", "01/~
$ id        <dbl> 35, 35, 35, 35, 35, 35, 35, 35, 35, 35, 35, 35, 35~
$ lat       <dbl> 36.07623, 36.07622, 36.07621, 36.07622, 36.07621, ~
$ long      <dbl> 24.87469, 24.87460, 24.87444, 24.87425, 24.87417, ~

Question 1:most popular places and when they are popular and find anomalies


#combine data
loyalty_data <- read_csv("MC2/loyalty_data.csv")
cc_data <- read_csv("MC2/cc_data.csv")
cc_data$last4ccnum<-as.character(cc_data$last4ccnum)
names(cc_data)<-c("timestamp","location","price","lastnum")
names(loyalty_data)<-c("timestamp","location","price","lastnum")
tran_data=rbind(cc_data,loyalty_data)





#clean tran_data
tran_data[str_detect(tran_data[, 2, drop = TRUE], 
                  "Katerina"), 2] <- as.character("Katerina's cafe")
tran_data$Timestamp <- date_time_parse(tran_data$timestamp,
                zone = "",
                format = "%m/%d/%Y")
tran_data$day <- as.factor(get_day(tran_data$Timestamp))

cleaned_tran <- tran_data %>%
  group_by(location,day) %>%
  summarise(activity=n())

#clean cc_data
cc_data[str_detect(cc_data[, 2, drop = TRUE], 
                  "Katerina"), 2] <- as.character("Katerina's cafe")

cc_data$Timestamp <- date_time_parse(cc_data$timestamp,
                zone = "",
                format = "%m/%d/%Y %H:%M")
cc_data$hour <- as.factor(get_hour(cc_data$Timestamp))
cc_data$day <- as.factor(get_day(cc_data$Timestamp))


cleaned_cc <- cc_data %>%
  group_by(location,hour) %>%
  summarise(activity=n())
#graph
p1<-ggplot(cleaned_tran, aes(y=activity,x=reorder(location,-activity))) + geom_bar_interactive(aes(tooltip=location),stat='identity')
girafe(
  ggobj = p1,
  width_svg = 6,
  height_svg = 6*0.618
)

As shown in the graph above, the most popular places are Katerinas cafe,Hippokampos,Guys Gyros and Brewve Been Served. We can further analysis when they are popular.


cleaned1_cc <- cc_data %>%
  filter(location=="Katerina's cafe"
         |location=="Hippokampos"
         |location=="Guy's Gyros"
         |location=="Brew've Been Served")%>%
  group_by(hour, location) %>%
  summarise(activity=n())
p3<-ggplot(cleaned1_cc, aes(x=hour, y=activity,color=location,group=location)) + geom_line_interactive(aes(tooltip=location),stat='identity')+
  theme(legend.position = "none")
girafe(
  ggobj = p3,
  width_svg = 6,
  height_svg = 6*0.618)

In this graph we can find that Brewve Been Served is only popular at 7-8. The rest time it is closed. Katerinas cafe is popular at both noon and night and is the most popular place among these 4 places. Hippokampos,Guys Gyros are similar. They are both popular at noon and night. But Hippokampos closed later and is popular till 10PM.Guys Gyros opened late at 1PM.


p2<-ggplot(cleaned_cc, aes(x=hour, y=activity,color=location,group=location)) + geom_line_interactive(aes(tooltip=location),stat='identity')+
  theme(legend.position = "none")
girafe(
  ggobj = p2,
  width_svg = 6,
  height_svg = 6*0.618
)

##combine gps longtitude and latitude data


gps_sf <- st_as_sf(gps, 
                   coords = c("long", "lat"),
                       crs= 4326)

gps_path <- gps_sf %>%
  group_by(id, day) %>%
  summarize(m = mean(Timestamp), 
            do_union=FALSE) %>%
  st_cast("LINESTRING")



##map


gps_path_selected <- gps_path %>%
  filter(day==6)
tmap_mode("view")
tm_shape(bgmap) +
  tm_rgb(bgmap, r = 1,g = 2,b = 3,
       alpha = NA,
       saturation = 1,
       interpolate = TRUE,
       max.value = 255) +
  tm_shape(gps_path_selected) +
  tm_lines()

In this map we can find that the 3 popular places Katerinas cafe,Guys Gyros and Brewve Been Served are all on the right bottom of the map. It is a new anomaly that staff likes to go to this right bottom column so much, regardless of the nearby restaurant like Chamelleon coffee and cup Ojoe. Another anomaly is that people like to go to the right side of the map so much, maybe it is the place where they live.
This map also explains some previous anomalies: Kronos mart is far from the Gastech so it explaines its low popularity for staff.

#choosing one time
time1=as.POSIXct("2014-01-10 08:00:00")


#find location of each car at that time
gps_sf$time <- as.POSIXct(gps_sf$Timestamp)
current_gps <- gps_sf %>%
  filter(time<time1)%>%
  group_by(id)%>%
  summarise(geometry[1],closest_time=max(time))
#building graph
tmap_mode("view")
tm_shape(bgmap) +
  tm_rgb(bgmap, r = 1,g = 2,b = 3,
       alpha = NA,
       saturation = 1,
       interpolate = TRUE,
       max.value = 255) +
  tm_shape(current_gps)+
  tm_dots(col="blue")

title: Dataviz_makeover_2
contents:
1 Critique of Visualization
The original visualization can be seen below.

1.1 Clarity
X and Y axis are messy and wrong:
They are imports and exports value which is numeric data, but they don't have tick marks or grid lines to indicate clear view of the actual imports and exports amount for different country. The 0 point should be at the beginning of x and y axis but in the graph is not.
Title is not concise:
The title is MERCHANDISE TRADE PERFORMANCE WITH MAJOR TRADING PARTNERS, 2020, it is very general and do not have sub-title to show further investigations from this graph.
The way it presents the net importers and exporters is not clear:
It uses the center point for each country to show whether they belong to importer or exporter. But for countries that have similar import value and export value they lay around the diagonal. So should have a clear way to indicate this.
Do not have data source and pictures to show further elucidation.
1.2 Aesthetic
Presentation of each data point is ugly:
Because the shape of each data point is too big and overlapping. It looks very messy. IT should be smaller and the round should be transparent to get rid of these problems.
Horrible color choice for import and export:
Should not use green and blue for two reverse concepts (Net importer and Net exporter).
Not interactive:
Do not have further information or other graph when click on each country.
2 Alternative Design
The proposed design is as follows.

2.1 Clarity
Show the data clearly by tooltips:
Use Tooltips to clearly show import and export value and their percentile. Also create a pie chart for each country to show this.
Use good title to indicate the investigations:
Use title and sub-title to show the trend of this graph concisely. Also show the data source.
Use pie chart to clearly show the percentage import and export takes.
2.2 Aesthetic
Presentation is more beautiful:
Each data point has smaller shape and is transparent so have a clear view.
Use appropriate colors:
Use distinctive color for net importer and net exporter. And show different colors for total trade values while import>export and import<export. Makes it very easy to classify the type for each country
Data source and image source is included:
By using image can emphasize the information we want to convey in this graph and makes it clear and easy to read this graph.
3 Step-by-step Guide
1 Import the data into Tableau Prep Builder. Click on Cleaned with data interpreter and drag the T1 and T2 into the panel. Rename them with Import and Export. 
2 Add clean node for Import, custom split Variables column with ( and rename it with Country. Remove the previous column. Do the same with Export. 
3 Create Pivot1 after clean 1, select all months under Fields to the Pivoted Fields panel. Repeat for Pivot 2. 
4 Rename Pivot 1 names to Month and change data type to date. Rename Pivot 1 values to Import. Repeat for Exports. The name for pivot 2 values is Export. 
5 Do a join for Pivot 1 and 2 by Country=Country and Month=Month. 
6 Create a new clean node and remove the duplicate month and country. 
7 Add a new pivot after clean 3 and change imports and exports from columns to rows. Rename Pivot values to Trade Value (Thousand $) and Pivot type to Trade Type. 
8 Create an output node and run the flow. Name the file Monthly trade values.hyper. 
9 Open it in Tableau and use sheet 1 to create the first graph. Because the trade value is in thousand dollars we create a new column by multiply 1000 and name it Trade value. 
10 Add month and country to filter to get the 10 countries and year 2020. 
11 Create a new calculated field called Import and create Export with same code but type=Export. 
12 Create 2 new calculated field Total Value (Importer) and Total Value (Exporter). 
13 Create a new calculated field called Reference line. 
14 Drag export and import to column and row. And drag country to detail. 
15 Drag country to color and trade value to size. Change the Opacity to 75%. 
16 Drag the reference line to rows and change to dual Axis. 
17 Remove the color, shape of reference line. 
18 Right click on the reference line data point and click show trend lines. Adjust the size of reference line to 0 and trend line to appropriate looking. Now it only shows the trend line, which is our diagonal line. Hide the reference line axis. 
19 Create a new sheet, drag trade type to column and trade value to row. Change it to pie chart. 
20 Drag country to rows. Drag trade type and trade value to labels. Click on the filter to apply filter for all sheets. Change label trade value type to percentage of total and adjust the format to one digit. Drag country to column then will show percentage for each country. 
21 Back to sheet 1, drag the total value(importer) and total value(exporter) to tooltip. Edit the tooltip this way. 
22 Add country and total value(importer) and total value(exporter) to label and edit this way. 
23 Change the format of all value to $_B 
24 Add 2 annotations Net importer and Net exporter at the top left and bottom right. 
25 Edit the tile and sub title 
26 Add image and adjust the annotations and axis to get best presentation. 
4 Derived Insights
Taiwan is the extreme importer in 2020. Its import value takes 66.6% of total which means Taiwan is heavily relying on importing. At the same time, Hong Kong is the extreme exporter with 92.4% of total trade value is export. This shows Hong Kong is a very extreme area that seldom import but largely export goods.
China is biggest trading region with $136.2B total trade amount in 2020. And the export and import value is balanced for China. Malaysia has the second biggest trade value of $103.5B in 2020 and United States is the third with $102.4B in 2020.
Out of these 9 areas, 6 are net exporter while 3 are net importer. For the 3 net importers (Taiwan, Japan, Malaysia), Taiwan and Japan are island area which may lead to its lack of goods.

title: DataViz Makeover 1
description: This is a graph for merchandise trade of 6 regions, 2019-2021
contents:
1 Critique of Visualisation
The original visualisation can be seen below.

1.1 Clarity
Area chart makes it difficult to gage height. Two areas overlap and looks messy. Also, area chart doesn't show the data is a time-series data.
Title (2019-2020) and content (2019-2021) are not consistent.
Inconsistent Y-axis for different countries makes it hard to compare. For e.g.Some use 0-6M, some use 0-8M, some use 0-2M.
Secondary axis makes it hard to compare import and export data.
X-axis should use title Year of period as it only shows Year.
Data source not included.
Annotations are not used meaning this is no further elucidation for the graph.
1.2 Aesthetic
Format of axes: vertical title of Y-axis
Horrible color choice for import and export, not distinctive.
Ugly font size: Title is smaller than the country name.
Gird lines already out the graph.
No any picture included.
2 Alternative Design
The proposed design is as follows.

2.1 Clarity
Use line chart to show the time-series data, which shows the trend clearly.
Different regions use the same Y axis and they are in the same row, makes it easy and clear to compare. Also imports and exports use the same axis, makes it easy to compare these 2 categories.
Have title and sub-title to emphasize the key observations.
Have trend line to show the important date and use annotations to show details.
2.2 Aesthetic
Call-outs with images aid cognition.
Tick marks are used for years.
Data source and image source is included.
3 Proposed Visualisation
Please view the interactive visualisation on Tableau Public here.
4 Step-by-step Guide
1 Import the data into Tableau. 
2 Use prep cleaning 
3 Use Tableau to pivot the data in sheet. Do the same with T2.
4 Change the relationship for T1 and T2 like this. 
5 Change the data type and name for T1 and T2 in the worksheet. 
6 Use filter to get the country and date we want. 
7 Drag the columns and rows from data. 
8 Choose line graph. 
9 Change date(year) to date(month) 
10 Add title, sub-title, sources 
11 Change Y axis, use the same range for imports and exports, then hide one of the Y axis. 
12 Remove the title for X axis and Y axis. 
13 Change format to get the tick marks for both axes. 
14 Add grid lines for row. 
15 Hide field labels country. 
16 Change the region names. Remove Thousand dollars. 
17 Add a reference line. 
18 Change the reference line looking and add marks. 
19 Create a dashboard and drag the graph into it. 
20 Set the labels floating. 
21 Insert an image object and adjust its size. 
22 Adjust the graph size for better looking and now it looks like this. 
5 Derived Insights
In 2020 Mar, when COVID-19 outbroke, all 6 regions get influenced and their imports and exports amount both declined. After a quarter, merchandise trade for these 6 regions begin to recover.
Hong Kong's exports rise sharply after May 2020, in Mar 2021, it has reached 7.4M thousand dollars.
Taiwan's imports rise sharply after for the whole period, it is only slightly influenced by COVID-19. In Mar 2021 it has reached 5.4M thousand dollars.
Hong Kong's exports is much higher than imports. While Taiwan's imports is much higher than exports.
